<body>
  <header>
    <div class="wrap" style="background:transparent;box-shadow:none;padding:0">
      <h1>How to Host an Unreal Engine Game Online — Quick Guide</h1>
      <p class="lead">A compact, practical checklist for getting a playable Unreal multiplayer game online: listen server, dedicated server, cloud host, matchmaking, NAT, and packaging notes.</p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <main class="wrap">
    <section>
      <strong class="pill">Step 1</strong>
      <h2>Decide your server model</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Listen server</strong> — one player hosts; easiest for small tests and P2P-style games.</li>
        <li><strong>Dedicated server</strong> — separate program runs on a server machine; required for stable multiplayer, authoritative server, and most live games.</li>
        <li><strong>Peer-to-peer with relay/NAT punchthrough</strong> — use if you want players to connect without port forwarding but don't want a true dedicated server (needs relay service).</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <strong class="pill">Step 2</strong>
      <h2>Make sure your game supports networking</h2>
      <p class="note">Unreal is network-ready, but you must design gameplay with replication and authority in mind.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Use replicated variables and <code>ReplicateMovement</code> where appropriate.</li>
        <li>Perform server authoritative actions (spawn damage, winning conditions) on the server.</li>
        <li>Test with multiple clients locally using the PIE "New Editor Window (PIE)" multiple clients option or packaged builds.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <strong class="pill">Step 3</strong>
      <h2>Build a dedicated server (recommended)</h2>
      <ol>
        <li>In Project Settings &gt; Packaging: enable building a server target (Linux servers are common for production).</li>
        <li>Package a server build:
          <pre>// Example packaging targets (conceptual)
ue4editor.exe MyProject.uproject -run=Cook -Target=MyGame
Run UnrealBuildTool to create a Server target (e.g., MyGameServer)</pre>
        </li>
        <li>On Linux you typically produce a headless executable; on Windows a <code>-server</code> command-line run is possible.</li>
      </ol>
      <p class="note">Production servers are usually Linux (cost, stability, tooling); during dev you can run a Windows server locally for quick tests.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <strong class="pill">Step 4</strong>
      <h2>Typical server launch commands</h2>
      <p class="note">Examples — adjust paths and map names for your project.</p>

      <h3>Linux dedicated server (example)</h3>
      <pre>cd /home/ubuntu/MyGame/Binaries/Linux
./MyGameServer-Linux-Shipping MyMap?listen -log -Port=7777</pre>

      <h3>Windows dedicated server (example)</h3>
      <pre>MyGameServer.exe MyMap?listen -server -log -Port=7777</pre>

      <p class="note">Common default port for Unreal is <code>7777</code> UDP (game traffic). You may need additional ports for query, web, or admin interfaces.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <strong class="pill">Step 5</strong>
      <h2>Networking basics: ports & NAT</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Open port(s)</strong> on the server's firewall and cloud security group (e.g., UDP 7777).</li>
        <li>If your host is a player machine (listen server) you must set up <strong>port forwarding</strong> on their router for the chosen port(s).</li>
        <li><strong>NAT traversal</strong> (STUN/TURN or relay) is required to avoid forcing players to forward ports. Use a matchmaking/relay provider if you want seamless connections.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <strong class="pill">Step 6</strong>
      <h2>Matchmaking, lobbies and presence</h2>
      <p class="note">For friendly UX you'll want matchmaking + presence so players can find games without IPs.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Epic Online Services (EOS)</strong> — free SDK for auth, lobbies, matchmaking, and presence (works cross-platform).</li>
        <li><strong>Steamworks</strong> — if you publish on Steam, use Steam matchmaking + lobby system (requires Steam integration).</li>
        <li>Other backends: PlayFab, GameSparks, AWS GameLift — provide matchmaking and server fleets.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <strong class="pill">Step 7</strong>
      <h2>Host on cloud or game server provider</h2>
      <p class="note">Options — each has tradeoffs (cost, control, complexity):</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Self-managed VPS/VM (AWS EC2, Google Cloud, Azure)</strong>
          <ul><li>Spin up a VM, open ports, upload the dedicated server, run it. Scale with autoscaling and a load balancer if you run many servers.</li></ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Managed game server providers (PlayFab, GameLift, Multiplay, Nodecraft, etc.)</strong>
          <ul><li>Offer easier scaling, matchmaking hooks, and lifecycle management for game servers.</li></ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Container approach</strong> — run dedicated servers in Docker/Kubernetes for scale/automation (CI/CD, autoscaling).</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <strong class="pill">Step 8</strong>
      <h2>Security & reliability checklist</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Validate all client inputs on the server (never trust the client).</li>
        <li>Use encryption for sensitive data (auth tokens, player data).</li>
        <li>Monitor logs and metrics; plan for restarts/crash recovery.</li>
        <li>Automate deployments with CI (GitHub Actions, GitLab CI) to avoid manual errors.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <strong class="pill">Step 9</strong>
      <h2>Testing your multiplayer setup</h2>
      <ol>
        <li>Local multi-client testing (PIE) &amp; packaged client + local server.</li>
        <li>Remote testing: run a server on a cloud VM and connect a client from your home machine / friend machine.</li>
        <li>Simulate latency and packet loss (tc/netem on Linux or network simulator tools) to see how your game behaves.</li>
      </ol>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Quick cheatsheet / commands</h2>
      <pre>// Build &amp; run dedicated server (concept)
// Linux: build shipping server binary, upload to VM, then:
./MyGameServer-Linux-Shipping MyMap?listen -log -Port=7777

// Start client and connect:
MyGameClient.exe 127.0.0.1:7777
MyGameClient.exe <public-ip>:7777</pre>
      <p class="note">If clients fail to connect, check server firewall, cloud security groups, and router port forwarding. Also check if the server listens on the right interface (0.0.0.0).</p>
    </section>

    <footer>
      <strong>Start small:</strong> try a local dedicated server first, then move to a cheap cloud VM to test remote connections, then add matchmaking/relay when you want scale and seamless player experience.
    </footer>
  </main>
</body>
